<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>BIS SELECT COMMITTEE INQUIRY INTO ROYAL MAIL PRIVATISATION</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PROTECT: Policy and Commercial </span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">BIS SELECT COMMITTEE INQUIRY INTO ROYAL MAIL PRIVATISATION</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">HM GOVERNMENT EVIDENCE PAPER</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">BACKGROUND</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: The Universal Postal Service</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government’s primary objective in relation to postal services is to secure the un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iversal postal service in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which is part of the social and economic fabric of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Under European law, the UK Government is legally obliged to ensure that there is a universal postal service in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, five days a week at affordable prices. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Through the Postal Services Act 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (“the PSA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”), the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government strengthened this requirement to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure the provision of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a universal postal service six days a week at affordable prices in accordance with a uniform tariff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to all 29 million addresses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail is the only company currently capable of providing this service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a thriving Royal Mail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is therefore necessary to enable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Government to achieve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its primary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">objective. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RATIONALE: T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he Need for Reform</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The digital revolution has presented significant challenges for Royal Mail.  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">email </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the internet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has resulted in a decline in the number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">addressed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">letters being sent,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">down by 27% since 2007</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Meanwhile, the parcels market is growing rapidly due to the increasing popularity of online shopping. This changing market presents both challenges to the financial sustainability of the universal postal service and opportunities which Royal Mail must exploit in order to secure a successful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">future. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Report to Parliament, ‘Royal Mail: Sale of Shares’</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, published on 10 July 2013 sets out the background to the Government’s postal sector reforms. The sale of shares follows the passage of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PSA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which lifted restrictions on Royal Mail’s ownership, allowing Government to sell shares in Royal Mail.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Through the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PSA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Government implemented a series of reforms in line with the recommendations of the Independent Review of the Postal Services Sector led by Richard Hooper, published in 2008</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and updated in 2010</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These included the establishment of a new regulatory regime for postal services, with Ofcom as regulator, and enabled Royal Mail’s historic pension deficit to be transferred to Government.  The Act also lifted restrictions on the sale of Royal Mail share</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so that it could in future access private sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Royal Mail and the Post Office Limited (“Post Office”) were separated in 2012.  The Post Office is not for sale.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ACCESS TO PRIVATE CAPITAL AND COMMERCIAL DISCIPLINES</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="OLE_LINK38"></a><a name="OLE_LINK39"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The action that Government has taken on regulation and pensions, coupled with the hard work of Royal Mail employees and management on the modernisation programme, has produced results. Royal Mail's </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mails business has been profitable with positive cash flows in the last two years, following losses in 5 of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">previous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> years.</span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail’s results for the financial year ending 31 March 2013 were an improvement on the previous year</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Revenue of £9,146 million was £382 million (+5%) ahead of the same period to March 2012.  Operating profit after transformation costs grew </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to £403 million </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from £152 million with profit margin increasing from 1.7% to 4.4% on a like-for-like basis.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><a name="OLE_LINK1"></a><a name="OLE_LINK2"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the road to sustainability, but much remains to be done.  Royal Mail must continue the process of modernisation and transformation and must be able to invest to grasp new business opportunities.  </span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Richard Hooper’s updated report in 2010 concluded that private sector capital was needed to:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure that Royal Mail had cash available when needed to fund accelerated modernisation;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inject private sector disciplines into the business;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reduce the risk of political interference in commercial decisions; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">encourage Royal Mail to develop a more customer-focused commercial strategy and diversification for the digital age.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail is one of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s largest companies, employing over 150,000 people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with a turnover of £9 billion.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should be able to access flexible capital so that it can continue to modernise and innovate, invest and seize opportunities presented by new markets such as the rapid growth of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> online shopping.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Deutsche Post, for example, has invested €700 million on automation in the past two years and will be investing a further €750 million by 2014 on parcels automation.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government funding is subject to State Aid rules and is neither fast e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nough nor flexible enough to facilitate the rapid investment and innovation that Royal Mail needs to thrive.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A Royal Mail run on a fully commercial basis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with real commercial freedom </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has the capacity to be cash generative, profitable and able to raise the investment capital that it needs from the private sector.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It should not need to call on public sector funding w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hich is better spent elsewhere.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WHAT </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GOVERNMENT HAS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> ANNOUNCED</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government published the objectives for a sale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in a W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ritten </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tatement to Parliament </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on 25 April 2013:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“The Government will secure the universal postal service for the benefit of all users by securing Royal Mail’s future through the introduction of private sector capital and associate disciplines. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This will be achieved through:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivering a sale of shares in Royal Mail within this Parliament;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">creating an employee share scheme that, as Parliament has decided, will lead to at least 10% of the company in employee ownership, to drive stronger staff engagement; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivering a financial outcome for the taxpayer, which when considered in the context of the overarching policy objective, represents overall value for money.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The "Royal Mail: Sale of Shares" report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">laid in Parliament on 10 July</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> confirmed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Government's</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> decision to move </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">toward</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> an Initial Public Offering (IPO)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of Royal Mail shares </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this financial year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Intention to Float announce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was issued on 12 September 2013, followed by the announcement of the price range, offer size range and offer launch on 27 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">September</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Company also published its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Prospectus</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">27 September. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These announcements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> confirmed that:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The institutional offer and the retail offer opened on 27 September </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">expected to close on 8 October 2013. Conditional dealings are expected to commence on 11 October and Admission to the London Stock Exchange is expected to take place on 15 October.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMG intends to dispose of a majority stake including, leaving HMG with a residual holding between 30%. and 49.9%. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Base </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Offer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">size will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">between 40.1 per cent. and 52.2 per cent. of Royal Mail’s share capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with additional s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hares representing up to 15 per cent. of the Base Offer also being made available </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-allotment Arrangements.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 10 per cent of Royal Mail shares will be made available for free to around 150,000 eligible UK-based Royal Mail employees under the Employee Share Scheme. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xpected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Offer price range </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">260p to 330p per Share, implying a market capitalisation on Admission of between £2,600 million and £3,300 million.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HM Government currently envisages that around 70 per cent. of the Base Offer will be allocated to institutional investors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">IPO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> includes a Retail offer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, enabling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">members of the public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> located in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to apply for shares through intermediaries or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">direct to Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The minimum application size for members of the public is £750. Eligible Royal Mail employees can apply through the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Employee Priority Offer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which has a minimum application size of £500. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail intends to propose a final dividend only, to be paid in July 2014, of £133 million. In subsequent financial years Royal Mail intends to pursue a progressive dividend policy having regard to the normalised earnings progression of the Group. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SAFEGUARDS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Universal Postal Service</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PSA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> enshrines in law the minimum requirements of the service, including: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivery of letters six days per week to every address in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (parcels five days per week) at uniform and affordable prices; and </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ree services for the blind.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The PSA requires that the universal service be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">uniform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> throughout the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so it is not possible for the universal service to be subject to ‘zonal pricing’ or different standards in different parts of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Changes to the uniform nature of the service would require new primary legislation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hanges to the minimum requirements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would require the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> agreement of Parliament via the affirmative resolution procedure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ofcom sets out a wide set of services and standards for the universal service in its Universal Service Order.  This must include the minimum requirements that are enshrined in the PSA but can also include things like quality of service standar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ds. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ofcom can only amend the Universal Service Order following a review of user needs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Beyond that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here is no obligation to conduct a review of user needs, save for the first one which was required within 18 months of Ofcom assuming responsibility for postal servic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es.  This was completed in March</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 2013 and Ofcom concluded that the postal market was meeting the reasonable needs of users and therefore proposed no changes.  Ofcom has indicated that it will keep user needs under review as the postal market develops. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">'s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">designated universal service provider (DUSP) and is obliged to provide the universal service to the standards set out by Ofcom. Neither Royal Mail nor any new shareholders will be able to reduce the number of days of delivery, stop delivering to rural areas or stop offering free services for the blind.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The universal service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will continue to be regulated by Ofcom, which has a duty under the Act and under European law to ensure that the universal service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – which includes 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> class stamps -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> remain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> affordable.  Ofcom has introduced a safeguard price cap on 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> class stamps, large letters and parcels up to 2kg.  Increases in the price cap are pegged to CPI, in line with the recommendation of the BIS Committee report on stamp prices in 1 March 2013</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  Ofcom have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also made clear that they will continue to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">monitor the prices of universal services to ensure they remain affordable. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Act gives Ofcom a duty to secure the provision of sufficient access points (e.g. post boxes) to meet the reasonable needs of users.  In June 2013 Ofcom increased protection for rural post boxes by requiring that Royal Mail provide a post box within half of mile of at least 98% of the ‘delivery points’ (usually the letter box of an address) nationally.  For the remaining 2%, Royal Mail must provide sufficient post boxes or other means of access to meet the reasonable needs of those users, having regard to the costs and practicalities of doing so. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Concern has been raised about the possibility of Royal Mail relocating delivery offices to inconvenient locations for consumers. Ofcom has placed a regulatory condition on Royal Mail requiring it to offer customers the choice of redelivery to the home or collection from a Post Office, Delivery Office or other collection point approved by Ofcom. With other 1,300 Royal Mail Delivery Offices and over 11,500 Post Offices in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, consumers will always have a convenient collection point for their parcels.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Free services for the armed forces are not dependent on Royal Mail ownership. The Ministry of Defence fully reimburses Royal Mail for the provision of these services and this would not change following an IPO.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With regards to competition in the postal market, the Government’s position is clear: competition can bring benefits to consumers but cannot be at the expense of the universal postal service.  The Act gives Ofcom a primary duty to carry out its functions in relation to postal services in a way that it considers will secure provision of the universal postal service.  In March Ofcom published a statement on its approach to regulating end-to-end competition</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and made clear that, should a threat to the universal service arise from such competition, it has the po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wers to take necessary action. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ofcom also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">said</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that it will initiate a review of end-to-end competition towards the end of 2015 if it has not done so already.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Post Office </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Post Office is not part of the Royal Mail sale.  The Post Office will remain in public ownership with the exception of a possible future move to a mutual ownership structure.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Royal Mail and Post Office Limited (POL) were separated into sister companies in April 2012.  POL now has an independent Board and freedom to focus on its own business and strategies to grow its revenues and transform its network.  POL is stronger and more sustainable as an independent business, and its first full annual report showed that revenues had grown, and that the company has stabilised the network following more than two decades of continual decline.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With more than 11,500 branches, the Post Office network is the largest retail network in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. In January 2012 Royal Mail and POL signed a ten-year business agreement that ensures Royal Mail products continue to be available at all post offices. This long-term agreement provides significant business certainty for the two companies and the sale of shares in Royal Mail will not impact the terms of the agreement or ongoing relationship.  Royal Mail’s Chief Executive has publicly stated that it would be “unthinkable” for the two businesses not to continue working together for the long-term, and the actions the Government is taking to ensure the long-term sustainability of the Post Office network – in particular by investing in extending opening hours and further improving customer service - will ensure that it continues to be a crucial partner for Royal Mail in the years to come.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although Royal Mail is POL’s largest customer, the majority of POL’s revenues are from other sources, including its successful financial services offering, continued access to a wide range of government services, and its telephony business.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Over the course of this Parliament, Government is providing £1.34 billion to both maintain the network with at least 11,500 branches, and to provide for the transformation of up to 6,000 branches under the Network Transformation programme.  To date, over 1,800 sub postmasters have committed to modernising their branches, and in July 2012, the BIS Committee found that the “Network Transformation reforms are necessary” and “in the right direction”.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RELATED DOCUMENTS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Report to Parliament: Royal Mail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of Shares, 10 July 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Intention to Float announcement, 12 September 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; fo